In this article, President Donald J. Trump proclaims February 2020 as American Heart Month. He acknowledges that heart disease is the leading cause of death in the United States and expresses condolences to the families affected by it. The article highlights several risk factors for heart disease, including high blood pressure, high cholesterol, physical inactivity, obesity, smoking, age, and family history. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention states that about half of all Americans have at least one of these risk factors. The article emphasizes the importance of behavior modification and lifestyle changes, such as maintaining a healthy diet, exercising regularly, moderating alcohol consumption, and avoiding smoking, in reducing the risk of heart disease. The article also mentions advancements in medical treatment options for heart conditions, including less invasive procedures and improved medications for conditions like high blood pressure, high cholesterol, and type 2 diabetes. The article recognizes the efforts of healthcare professionals, physical therapists, counselors, volunteers, and educators in supporting those with heart disease. President Trump calls for collective action to control cardiovascular health and offers support and motivation to friends and family members in their journey towards a healthier lifestyle. The article concludes by urging all Americans to prioritize their health and participate in National Wear Red Day on February 7, 2020, as a symbol of support in the fight against cardiovascular disease.